# JOINS EXAMPLES

===============

Assume two tables:

## EMPLOYEE TABLE
-------------------

| emp_id | emp_name | company_id |
| ------ | -------- | ---------- |
| 1      | Manoj    | C1         |
| 2      | Arun     | C2         |
| 3      | Ravi     | C1         |
| 4      | Kiran    | C3         |

## COMPANY TABLE
-----------------

| company_id | company_name |
| ---------- | ------------ |
| C1         | TCS          |
| C2         | Infosys      |
| C4         | Wipro        |



# INNER JOIN
------------

Definition:
Returns only matching records from both tables.

## QUERY
------------

SELECT e.emp_name, c.company_name
FROM employee e
INNER JOIN company c
ON e.company_id = c.company_id;


## RESULT
----------

| emp_name | company_name |
| -------- | ------------ |
| Manoj    | TCS          |
| Arun     | Infosys      |
| Ravi     | TCS          |

## EXPLANATION
---------------

* Only matching company_id values are returned
* Kiran is excluded (C3 not in company table)
* Wipro is excluded (no employee)



# LEFT JOIN
------------

Definition:
Returns all records from left table + matching from right table.

## QUERY
------------

SELECT e.emp_name, c.company_name
FROM employee e
LEFT JOIN company c
ON e.company_id = c.company_id;


## RESULT
------------

| emp_name | company_name |
| -------- | ------------ |
| Manoj    | TCS          |
| Arun     | Infosys      |
| Ravi     | TCS          |
| Kiran    | NULL         |

## EXPLANATION
---------------

* All employees are shown
* Kiran has no matching company → NULL
* Keeps all LEFT table data



# RIGHT JOIN
------------

Definition:
Returns all records from right table + matching from left table.




## QUERY
---------

SELECT e.emp_name, c.company_name
FROM employee e
RIGHT JOIN company c
ON e.company_id = c.company_id;


## RESULT
-----------

| emp_name | company_name |
| -------- | ------------ |
| Manoj    | TCS          |
| Arun     | Infosys      |
| Ravi     | TCS          |
| NULL     | Wipro        |

## EXPLANATION
--------------

* All companies are shown
* Wipro has no employee → NULL
* Keeps all RIGHT table data



# FULL OUTER JOIN
-----------------

Definition:
Returns all records from both tables.

## QUERY
----------


SELECT e.emp_name, c.company_name
FROM employee e
FULL OUTER JOIN company c
ON e.company_id = c.company_id;


## RESULT
---------

| emp_name | company_name |
| -------- | ------------ |
| Manoj    | TCS          |
| Arun     | Infosys      |
| Ravi     | TCS          |
| Kiran    | NULL         |
| NULL     | Wipro        |

## EXPLANATION
---------------

* Combines LEFT JOIN + RIGHT JOIN
* Shows all employees and all companies
* Missing matches are filled with NULL



# CROSS JOIN
------------

Definition:
Returns all possible combinations of rows.

## QUERY
--------

SELECT e.emp_name, c.company_name
FROM employee e
CROSS JOIN company c;


## RESULT (Example)
--------------------

| emp_name               | company_name |
| ---------------------- | ------------ |
| Manoj                  | TCS          |
| Manoj                  | Infosys      |
| Manoj                  | Wipro        |
| Arun                   | TCS          |
| Arun                   | Infosys      |
| Arun                   | Wipro        |
| ... (all combinations) |              |

## EXPLANATION
--------------

* Every employee is paired with every company
* Total rows = employees × companies
* No condition used



# FINAL UNDERSTANDING
----------------------

INNER JOIN   → Matching only
LEFT JOIN    → All left + match
RIGHT JOIN   → All right + match
FULL JOIN    → Everything
CROSS JOIN   → Multiplication of rows

